If you want it to be dynamic (e.g. pull the actual week number from the canonical data), you can do that too. Add this before the clauses list:

```python
# Pull checkpoint week from milestones if available
milestone_str = str(scope.get("milestones", ""))
checkpoint_week = "6"  # default
import re
week_match = re.search(r'week\s*(\d+)', milestone_str, re.IGNORECASE)
if week_match:
    checkpoint_week = week_match.group(1)

pilot_duration = "12 weeks"  # default
duration_match = re.search(r'(\d+)\s*week', milestone_str, re.IGNORECASE)
if duration_match:
    pilot_duration = f"{duration_match.group(1)} weeks"
```

Then make the clause dynamic:

```python
        (f"5.7  Project Governance",
         f"The parties shall conduct weekly status calls throughout the {pilot_duration} "
         f"project duration to review progress, risks, and blockers. A formal mid-project "
         f"review shall be conducted at the Week {checkpoint_week} checkpoint to assess "
         f"delivery against milestones and agree any scope or timeline adjustments. "
         f"Meeting minutes shall be circulated within 2 business days of each session."),
```

This way if a different SOW has a 16-week pilot with a week 8 checkpoint, it pulls those numbers automatically from the extracted data.
